<paragraph blockId="123.[189,495,1770,1796]" box="[189,495,1770,1796]" pageId="123" pageNumber="124">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,495,1770,1796]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="123" pageNumber="124" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,495,1770,1796]" pageId="123" pageNumber="124">Distribution and biology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="123.[189,1399,1817,2025]" pageId="123" pageNumber="124">
Known from NE 
<collectingCountry box="[399,515,1817,1843]" name="Myanmar" pageId="123" pageNumber="124">Myanmar</collectingCountry>
, N 
<collectingCountry box="[559,658,1817,1843]" name="Vietnam" pageId="123" pageNumber="124">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
and N 
<collectingCountry box="[749,857,1817,1843]" name="Thailand" pageId="123" pageNumber="124">Thailand</collectingCountry>
. In 
<collectingCountry box="[903,1017,1817,1843]" name="Myanmar" pageId="123" pageNumber="124">Myanmar</collectingCountry>
collected in a cloud forest with streams and swampy areas at an altitude of 
<quantity box="[717,812,1854,1880]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="123" pageNumber="124" unit="m" value="2000.0">2000 m</quantity>
. The specimen from 
<collectingCountry box="[1067,1166,1854,1880]" name="Vietnam" pageId="123" pageNumber="124">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
was collected by a Malaise trap near the Tram Ton Pass, the highest mountain pass of 
<collectingCountry box="[981,1080,1890,1916]" name="Vietnam" pageId="123" pageNumber="124">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
(
<quantity box="[1096,1190,1890,1916]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" pageId="123" pageNumber="124" unit="m" value="1900.0">1900 m</quantity>
), near Fan Si Pan mountain. The Malaise trap was set up in an area of montane forest disturbed by grazing buffaloes, containing muddy areas and small streams. Despite the cold and wet weather insects were still rather abundantly flying (C. van Achterberg, pers. comm).
</paragraph>
